# Chapter 11 — Guitars

A guitar is a string family instrument that carries the harmony
and the pulse at once, and that carries them from a single
person's two hands. That the harmony and the pulse fit into one
instrument's shape isn't a small thing — it's why a person with
one guitar can accompany a whole room of singers. The instrument
holds enough of the music inside itself that the other players
can stay in the same room without stepping on each other. Every
tune-family in the world that grew up around campfires,
kitchens, corners of streets, or church back rooms has some
version of the guitar in its middle. The instrument fills a role
that other instruments do parts of but not the whole of.

A guitar carries chord + rhythm + melody all in one pair of
hands. That's what makes it the campfire instrument. It's not
because guitars are simple; it's because they hold everything
at once.

## The three families of guitar

Guitars split into three families by construction and use:

- **Classical / nylon-string** — soft attack, wide neck, played
  fingerstyle. Home of the Spanish and Latin American traditions.
- **Acoustic steel-string** — brighter, louder, narrower neck.
  Home of folk, country, bluegrass, singer-songwriter.
- **Electric** — quiet on its own, loud through an amplifier.
  Home of blues, rock, funk, jazz-fusion, and everything after.

```scheme
(define guitar-families
  '((classical    \"nylon strings, wide neck, fingerstyle\")
    (acoustic     \"steel strings, mid neck, strum or fingerpick\")
    (electric     \"magnetic pickups, thin neck, amplified\")))

(map (lambda (fam) (car fam)) guitar-families)
;; => (classical acoustic electric)
```

Each family reads to a specific style-culture. A person handing
you a classical guitar is signaling a different tradition than
a person handing you a Stratocaster. Both are guitars; both are
different games.

## The parts of the instrument

```scheme
(define guitar-parts
  '((body       \"the resonator or the pickup platform\")
    (neck       \"the fretted length the fingers press\")
    (headstock  \"where the tuners live\")
    (bridge     \"where the strings anchor at the body end\")
    (nut        \"where the strings anchor at the neck end\")
    (frets      \"the metal bars that quantize pitch\")
    (pickups    \"electric only: transducers for magnetic strings\")))

(for-each (lambda (p) (display (car p))
                      (display \" — \")
                      (display (cadr p))
                      (newline))
          guitar-parts)
```

The instrument's shape carries its history: the frets
quantize pitch to the Western tuning grid (that's why blues
players *bend* strings — they're reaching for pitches between
the frets). The neck length decided the scale-length tradition
(short scale = warmer, long scale = brighter). Every luthier's
choice on the body shape is a choice about which frequencies
resonate loudest.

## Tuning

Standard tuning is E-A-D-G-B-E from low to high. Six strings,
five intervals: four perfect fourths and one major third.

```scheme
(define standard-tuning
  '((6 E2) (5 A2) (4 D3) (3 G3) (2 B3) (1 E4)))

(map cdr standard-tuning)
;; => (E2 A2 D3 G3 B3 E4)
```

Alternate tunings unlock voicings you can't reach in standard.
Open G (D-G-D-G-B-D), used in Delta blues and open-tuned
slide. DADGAD, used in Celtic instrumental music. Drop D
(D-A-D-G-B-E), used in modern rock. Each alternate tuning
opens a music the standard tuning can't quite reach. The
instrument is the same; the tuning is a lens.

## Playing techniques

- **Strumming** — sweep the pick or fingers across all strings.
  Chord-forward; the beat sits inside the strum pattern.
- **Fingerpicking** — pluck strings independently with thumb
  and fingers. Harmony and melody separate; the beat sits in
  the thumb.
- **Flatpicking** — a single pick moves across strings at high
  speed. Melody-forward; used in bluegrass and country lead.
- **Fingerstyle solo** — bass, chord, and melody all
  simultaneously from ten fingers. The classical and
  Chet-Atkins tradition.
- **Slide** — a glass or metal cylinder on one finger slides
  along the string instead of pressing on frets. Delta blues,
  Hawaiian, country.
- **Bending** — pressed fingers push a string sideways to
  raise its pitch by a semitone or a whole tone. Blues, rock.

Each technique is a game. A player who lives in fingerpicking
hears music in overlapping voices. A player who lives in
flatpicking hears music as running lines. Same instrument;
different game.

## A small chord progression

```scheme
(define twelve-bar-blues
  '((I  4) (IV 2) (I  2) (V  1) (IV 1) (I  2)))

(define G-blues
  (map (lambda (chord)
         (let ((roman (car chord))
               (bars  (cadr chord)))
           (list (case roman
                   ((I)  'G7)
                   ((IV) 'C7)
                   ((V)  'D7))
                 bars)))
       twelve-bar-blues))

G-blues
;; => ((G7 4) (C7 2) (G7 2) (D7 1) (C7 1) (G7 2))
```

Twelve bars of a G blues. Any guitarist in any of the three
families can play this. The classical player might voice the
chords fingerstyle. The acoustic player will strum in a
shuffle rhythm. The electric player will start bending notes
in the fills between chords. Same twelve bars, three different
kinds of music.

## Cross-instrument note

The guitar's role in a small ensemble — carrying chord and
pulse — is the same role a piano plays in a jazz trio (see
chapter 2 of this book). A guitarist and a pianist in the
same room have to negotiate: whose chord voicings are lead,
whose rhythmic pulse is leading, when the other lays out. The
negotiation is what makes the two-instrument accompaniment
sound composed rather than crowded. She reads the roles when
she scores for both.

## Editorial note

The guitar is the instrument most listeners have some
relationship to — even non-players know what a guitar sounds
like. That familiarity makes it hard to talk about
technically. She holds the technical vocabulary but stays
soft with it when a listener asks a first question. The
listener doesn't need to know what a scale length is to know
that this guitar sounds warm and that one sounds bright.
